# Enums
An enum (enumeration) is a special data type used to define a fixed set of named constants.
Why Use Enum?
- Improves readability
- Prevents invalid values
- Makes code type-safe
- Better than using constants (public static final)

Important methods:
values()	Returns all enum constants
valueOf()	Converts string to enum
ordinal()	Position (index)
name()	    Name of constant


# Generics and Diamond Operators
Generics: Generics allow you to write type-safe, reusable code by specifying the type of data a class, method, or interface can work with.

Why Use Generics?
- Avoid ClassCastException
- Improve type safety
- Eliminate explicit type casting
- Enable code reusability

